cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.CY, cs.SOC, cs.HC 

The paper utilizes social media data to analyze and compare lifestyle behaviors of people living in cities of different sizes, which falls under the categories of social computing (cs.SOC) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The use of matrix factor analysis as an unsupervised method suggests a focus on data analysis and machine learning (cs.SI), while the examination of mobility and work-rest patterns suggests a focus on cyber-physical systems (cs.CY) and systems and control (cs.SD).
